Introduction

Home values, prices and sales showed some of their strongest numbers since before the economic downturn a few years ago.Mortgage rates were downright cheap.

But there’s no guarantee favorable conditions for buying and borrowing will continue in the months ahead.

Consequently, it’s fair to ask the question: Can we predict housing prices with the help of some of the features in the Ames House pricing dataset?

Industry experts weigh in. Though no one can tell the future, their housing market forecast can help first-time home buyers make better decisions this year and next.

Data Exploration of Ames Housing Sales price Dataset

Number of records (Train set: 1460, Test set: 1459)

  1. Data Type differences between Train data set and Test data set

Datatype differs for some of the columns between Train data set and Test data set, Example Garage Area is Numeric type in Train data set where as String in Test data set due to NA values. Handled data type differences using Edit Meta data Module and Apply SQL Transformation module in Azure ML.

  1. Missing values in Train data set

Below fields have minimum missing values that may add value or reduce errors in predicticting sales price. Lot Frontage(numeric) : 259 missing values Masvnrtype(string):8 missing values Masvnrarea(numeric) :8 missing values Electrical(string) : 1 missing value Garage Type(string): 81 missing values Garage Yrblt(string) : 81 missing values Garage area(numeric): 81 missing values Garage cars(numeric) : 81 missing values

Below fields has huge missing values and that will not add any values to predict sales price.

Alley(string) : 1369 missing values PoolQc(string) :1453 missing values fence(string):1179 missing values miscfeature(strng) : 1406 missing valuess

Missing values are handled using convert to dataset module with replace custom option NA to 0 for Numeric and NA to None for string.

  1. Need to replace outliers ( I chose to replace with 95th percentile of data in each selected feature)

Feature Selection is performed in AzureML using FilterbasedFeature selection module. Top features selected in Azure ML with good score are provided below OverallQual , Neighborhood , GrLivArea , ExterQual , BsmtQual,KitchenQual,GarageArea, GarageYrBlt,MasVnrArea, TotalBsmtSF,LotArea, YearBlt and Yearremodelled,

OverallCond, Bedroomabvgr scores are less compared to above features but still added in the model to see if it can remove errors.

Selected below features based on Correlation analysis with SalePrice

OverallQual , Neighborhood, GrLivArea, ExterQual, LotFrontage, MasVnrArea, GarageYrBlt, BedroomAbvGr ,LotArea ,Overallcond, TotalBsmtSF and Age.

Age of the building is derived from YrSold, YearBlt and YrRemodelled.

Reference for Age is from Kaggle, Except Age rest all based on Correlation Analysis, Step AIC and Filter based Feature selection Module in Azure ML.

https://www.kaggle.com/mariopasquato/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/simplemodel

clean up the data , remove NA in the dataset and replace outlier wiht 95th percentile

# Convert below variables NA to 0 and make it as Integer in both Train and Test data


dataset1_train[(is.na(dataset1_train[,'LotFrontage'])),'LotFrontage']<- 0
dataset1_train[(is.na(dataset1_train[,'MasVnrArea'])),'MasVnrArea']<- 0
dataset1_train[(is.na(dataset1_train[,'GarageYrBlt'])),'GarageYrBlt']<- 0

dataset2_test[(is.na(dataset2_test[,'LotFrontage'])),'LotFrontage']<- 0
dataset2_test[(is.na(dataset2_test[,'MasVnrArea'])),'MasVnrArea']<- 0
dataset2_test[(is.na(dataset2_test[,'GarageYrBlt'])),'GarageYrBlt']<- 0


# Normalising Training Dataset

LogPrice <- log10(dataset1_train$SalePrice)
LogLotArea <- log10(dataset1_train$LotArea)
LogArea <- log10(dataset1_train$GrLivArea)
Bedroom <- dataset1_train$BedroomAbvGr
OverallCondition <- dataset1_train$OverallCond
External_Quality <- as.factor(dataset1_train$ExterQual)
Garage_area <- (dataset1_train$GarageArea)
bsmt_area <- (dataset1_train$TotalBsmtSF)
Age <- dataset1_train$YrSold - pmax(dataset1_train$YearBuilt,dataset1_train$YearRemodAdd)
Quality <- dataset1_train$OverallQual
Neighborhood <- as.factor(dataset1_train$Neighborhood)

# Replace Outlier in Train dataset with 95th percentile

Replace_outlier <- function(x){
  quantiles <- quantile( x, c(.95 ) )
  x[ x > quantiles[1] ] <- quantiles[1]
  x
}

LogLotArea <- Replace_outlier(LogLotArea)
Bedroom <- Replace_outlier(Bedroom)
OverallCondition <- Replace_outlier(OverallCondition)
LogArea <- Replace_outlier(LogArea)
Age <- Replace_outlier(Age)
Quality <- Replace_outlier(Quality)
LogPrice <- Replace_outlier(LogPrice)
Garage_area <- Replace_outlier(Garage_area)
bsmt_area <- Replace_outlier(bsmt_area)

# Move the data in to data frame

data_set_train=data.frame(LogLotArea,Bedroom,OverallCondition,External_Quality,LogArea,Age,Quality,Neighborhood,LogPrice,Garage_area,bsmt_area)

# Normalising Testing Dataset


LogLotArea <- log10(dataset2_test$LotArea)
LogArea <- log10(dataset2_test$GrLivArea)
Bedroom <- dataset2_test$BedroomAbvGr
OverallCondition <- dataset2_test$OverallCond
External_Quality <- as.factor(dataset2_test$ExterQual)
Garage_area <- (dataset2_test$GarageArea)
bsmt_area <- (dataset2_test$TotalBsmtSF)
Age <- dataset2_test$YrSold - pmax(dataset2_test$YearBuilt,dataset2_test$YearRemodAdd)
Quality <- dataset2_test$OverallQual
Neighborhood <- as.factor(dataset2_test$Neighborhood)

# Move data in to test data set frame.

data_set_test=data.frame(LogLotArea,Bedroom,OverallCondition,External_Quality,
                         LogArea,Age,Quality,Neighborhood,Garage_area,bsmt_area)

Before conversion LotFrontage, MasVnrArea, GarageYrBlt was “String” class due to NA values . Performed Log10 Normalization for salePrice, Lot Area and GrLivArea.

After Normalising the SalePrice to log10(salePrice), Normality histogram and QQ Plots looks better hence will use the Log10(SalePrice) for our analysis.

Plot the correlations

Let us will look at the correlations between the variables. The following display shows these correlations.

cols <- c("LogLotArea","Bedroom","OverallCondition","LogArea","Age","Quality",
                    "LogPrice","Garage_area","bsmt_area")
cors = cor(data_set_train[, cols], method = 'pearson')
## Loading required package: corrplot
require(corrplot)

corrplot.mixed(cors, upper = "ellipse")

According to the plots,

Log(SalePrice) is positively correlated to Quality,LogArea,Bedroom, Lot area, GarageArea and Bsmt_area.

SalePrice is Negatively correlated to Age (derived from YrSold, YrBlt and Yr Remodelled)

No Correlation with OverallCondition

Split the train dataset for 70% training the model and 30% testing the model

## Split the training dataset to train and test the model to compare actual vs predicted

set.seed(123)
smp_size <- floor(0.70 * nrow(data_set_train))
Data_split <- sample(seq_len(nrow(data_set_train)), size = smp_size)

dataset1_trainingData <- data_set_train[Data_split, ] 
dataset1_testingData <- data_set_train[-Data_split, ]

Create Linear Model

lm.model.1 = lm(LogPrice ~ LogLotArea+Bedroom+OverallCondition+External_Quality+LogArea+Age+Quality
                +Neighborhood+Garage_area+bsmt_area,  data = dataset1_trainingData)

summary(lm.model.1)
